## Q18 — The administrative scale: 70/72 territorial, 200 military, 2-4 per person

**Deuteronomy 32:8 textual triad.** Masoretic Text: *"lə-mispar **bnê Yiśrāʾēl**"* ("according to the number of the **sons of Israel**"). Septuagint (Rahlfs): *"kata arithmon **angelōn theou**"* ("according to the number of the **angels of God**"); some MSS read *"huiōn theou"* (sons of God). Qumran 4QDeutʲ: *"lə-mispar **bnê ʾĕlôhîm**"* ("according to the number of the **sons of God**"). The Qumran reading is the original (confirmed by Heiser, *Bibliotheca Sacra* 158, 2001); the MT is a Second Temple theological correction, anchoring the number to Jacob's 70-soul household (Gen 46:27, Ex 1:5) to obscure the divine-council referent.

**The 70/72 cluster.** Ugaritic KTU 1.4 VI:46 reads *"šbʿm bn ʾaṯrt"* — "the **70 sons of Athirat**" — at Baal's palace-feast (majority consensus: Smith, Wyatt, Pardee, Heiser). The number 70 then propagates: 70 nations in Genesis 10 (Shem 26 + Ham 30 + Japheth 14); 70 Israelites to Egypt (Gen 46:27); 70 elders (Num 11:16); 70 disciples sent (Luke 10:1, var. 72); **Targum Ps.-Jonathan on Deut 32:8**: *"He cast lots with the seventy angels, the princes of the nations"*; Pirkei DeRabbi Eliezer §24: *"the seventy angels who surround the throne of His glory…seventy nations…seventy languages"*; 1 Enoch 89:59 (Animal Apocalypse): "seventy shepherds" set over Israel. **3 Enoch 17:8; 18:2; 30:2 give the variant 72** (matching LXX Gen 10's 72 nations with Cainan). Daniel 10:13, 20-21 instantiates the schema with three named *sarim*: prince of Persia, prince of Greece, Michael as prince of Israel. **70 began as symbolic (7×10 = totality) but became traditionally fixed across roughly two millennia of West Semitic and post-biblical literature.**

**The 200 Watchers of Hermon.** 1 Enoch 6:6 (Ge'ez *hulättu məʾət* / Aramaic 4Q201 1 iii *maʾtên*): "they were in all **two hundred** who descended in the days of Jared on Mount Hermon." 1 Enoch 6:7 names **20 leaders** (Sêmîazâz, Arâkîba, Râmêêl, Kôkabîêl, Tâmîêl, Râmîêl, Dânêl, Êzêqêêl, Barâqîjâl, Asâêl, Armârôs, Batârêl, Anânêl, Zaqîêl, Samsâpêêl, Satarêl, Tûrêl, Jômjâêl, Sariêl, +1 from Aramaic) explicitly identified as *"chiefs of tens"* (6:8 Ge'ez *ʾəllu maxabəra ʿaśərtu*; Aramaic *רישי עשרתא*). **The structure is unambiguous: 20 decadarchs × 10 = 200 total rebel force.** Each named chief teaches a distinct technology (1 Enoch 8): Azazel — metallurgy/weapons/cosmetics; Semjaza — enchantments; Baraqijal — astrology; Kokabel — constellations; Ezeqeel — clouds; Shamsiel — solar signs; Sariel — lunar course. This is a **military command structure projected onto rebel angels with technological specializations**.

**Per-person Islamic angelic surveillance.** Q 82:10-12 names *ḥāfiẓīn* (keepers) and *kirāman kātibīn* (noble recorders); Q 13:11 names *muʿaqqibāt* (successive guardians) before and behind; Q 50:17-18 names the *mutalaqqiyāni* (two receivers, right and left), called *Raqīb* and ʿAtīd. **Bukhārī 555** crystallizes the shift structure: *"al-malāʾikatu yataʿāqabūna fīkum, malāʾikatun bi-l-layli wa-malāʾikatun bi-n-nahār, wa-yajtamiʿūna fī ṣalāti l-fajri wa-ṣalāti l-ʿaṣr"* — angels relieve each other at the Fajr and ʿAṣr prayers, ascending to report. Tafsīr synthesis (Ibn Kathīr, al-Rāzī, Maʿārif al-Qurʾān): **2 ḥafaẓa by day + 2 by night + 2 kirāmān kātibīn (right/left) = 4 active at any time, up to 6 in rotation**, plus the *qarīn-malak* and post-mortem Munkar/Nakīr.

**The architectural logic is consistent across three scales:** macro-territorial (70/72 angels over nations), meso-military (200 in 20×10 decads), and micro-personal (2+2 in day/night shifts). All three exhibit decimal/septenary scaffolding and **fixed liturgical transition points** (Babel for the 70; Hermon for the 200; Fajr/ʿAṣr for the per-person shifts). Null: no tradition gives a total "all angels assigned to Earth" number — the 200 is the rebel force, the 70/72 is the territorial division, and per-person rotations bring the total into the billions but are never aggregated.

**Confidence VH** for individual numbers; **H** for the architectural interpretation.

