## Q19 — The Arabic four-layer model and 28 nations: a multi-species pre-Adamic cosmology

The classical sources preserve a real but **non-systematic** multi-layer taxonomy. Al-Ṭabarī's *Tafsīr* on al-Baqara 30 (via al-Ḍaḥḥāk ← Ibn ʿAbbās) gives the canonical narrative: *"awwalu man sakana al-arḍa al-jinn, fa-afsadū fīhā wa-safakū fīhā al-dimāʾ…fa-baʿatha llāhu ilayhim Iblīsa, fa-qatalahum…ḥattā alḥaqahum bi-jazāʾir al-buḥūr wa-aṭrāf al-jibāl"* — "the first to inhabit the earth were the jinn; they corrupted and shed blood; God sent Iblīs against them, who killed them and drove them to the islands of the seas and edges of the mountains." Crucially, the same chain identifies **Iblīs as from a tribe of angels called al-Ḥinn**, created from *nār al-samūm*. Ibn Kathīr (*al-Bidāya wa'l-Nihāya* 1/55) preserves the two-stage account verbatim: *"khuliqat al-jinnu qabla Ādam, wa-kāna qablahum fī al-arḍi **al-Ḥinnu wa-l-Binnu**, fa-sallaṭa llāhu al-jinna ʿalayhim fa-qatalūhum wa-ajlawhum ʿanhā wa-abādūhum minhā"* — Ḥinn and Binn preceded the Jinn, who exterminated them.

The full four-layer list (**al-Ḥinn / al-Binn / al-Ṭimm / al-Rimm**) appears together only in **Ibn ʿĀshūr's *al-Taḥrīr wa'l-Tanwīr* 1/228**, who explicitly identifies *al-Ṭimm wa-l-Rimm* with Persian myth and compares them to the **Greek Titans** — a medieval Arab scholar consciously identifying this as cross-cultural mythological material. Sibṭ Ibn al-Jawzī's *Mirʾāt al-Zamān* adds a narrative layer: a prophet named Yūsuf was sent to the al-Ḥinn/al-Binn, who refused him; angels then exiled them after a thousand-year occupation.

**Al-Masʿūdī's 28 nations** appear in *Akhbār al-Zamān* (the surviving fragment of his lost 30-volume work, not *Murūj al-Dhahab* directly): *"kānat al-jumlatu thamāniyan wa-ʿishrīna ummatan bi-izāʾi al-manāzili al-ʿāliya allatī yaḥulluhā al-qamar…khuliqat min amzijatin mukhtalifatin aṣluhā al-māʾ wa-l-hawāʾ wa-l-nār wa-l-arḍ"* — "the total was 28 nations corresponding to the lunar mansions…created from differing mixtures of water, air, fire, and earth, so they are of disparate forms." The extant text describes ~12 of the 28 by physical form: tall blue winged beings with crackling speech; lion-bodied bird-headed creatures; two-faced multi-legged bird-speakers; jinn proper; dog-shaped mutterers; chest-mouthed whistlers; winged-legged-tailed serpents; **half-bodied one-eyed one-armed one-legged hoppers with crane-speech (= Nasnās)**; turtle-backed clawed long-horned wolf-howlers; two-headed lion-faced beings; round-faced white-haired cow-tailed spitters; all-female wind-impregnated melodious beings. **The remaining ~16 are lost with the rest of the work.** Al-Masʿūdī himself attributes the cosmology to **"what the Indians, Persians, and Greeks claim"** — flagging it as comparative-mythological synthesis, not ḥadīth.

**The pre-Adamic jinn built a civilization.** Al-Masʿūdī: *"mufarriqūna ʿalā iḥdā wa-ʿishrīna qabīla"* (21 tribes), with a kingship system including a named monarch **Shamāʾīl b. Aras-Jinn**, a 5,000-year political history, inter-tribal warfare, and Iblīs as one of their warlords. The jinn-class fate: **defeated by angels under Iblīs, displaced to seas and mountains, but extant** (revealed in Sūrat al-Jinn).

**The Nasnās are euhemerized degeneration.** Multiple chains converge: *"al-Nasnās ibn Umaym ibn ʿImlīq ibn Yalmaʿ ibn Lāwidh ibn Sām ibn Nūḥ"* — descendants of Shem via Umaym, eponymous king of **Wabār** (archaeologically associated with Ubar / Iram dhāt al-ʿImād in the Empty Quarter). Al-Hamdānī (via Yāqūt): *"kānat Wabār akthar al-arḍīn khayran wa-akhṣabahā…kānū qawman jabābiratan dhawī ajsām, fa-lam yaʿrifū ḥaqq niʿam Allāhi taʿālā, fa-baddala llāhu khalqahum wa-ṣayyarahum nasnāsan"* — "Wabār was the richest of lands…they were a race of giants with great bodies; they did not recognize God's favor, so God transformed their forms and made them into Nasnās." Al-Masʿūdī (*Murūj*) credits **Umaym as the first architect**: *"awwalu man ibtanā al-bunyāna wa-rafaʿa al-ḥīṭāna wa-qaṭaʿa al-ashjāra wa-saqqafa al-suqūfa"* — "the first to construct buildings, raise walls, cut trees, and roof structures."

**Nasnās descriptions across primary zoological/cosmological literature.** Al-Qazwīnī (*ʿAjāʾib al-Makhlūqāt*): *"li-kulli wāḥidin minhum niṣfu badanin wa-niṣfu raʾsin wa-yadun wa-rijl, ka-annahu insānun shuqqa niṣfayn, yaqfizu ʿalā rijlin wāḥidatin qafzan shadīdan"* — "each has half a body, half a head, one arm, and one leg, as though split in two; hops violently on one leg" — found in the islands of the China Sea. Al-Damīrī (*Hayāt al-Hayawān* 2/479) reports a ḥadīth: *"inna ḥayyan min ʿĀd ʿaṣaw rasūlahum fa-masakhahum llāhu nasnāsan, li-kulli insānin minhum yadun wa-rijlun min shiqqin wāḥid, yanquzūna kamā yanquzu al-ṭāʾir, wa-yarʿawna kamā tarʿā al-bahāʾim"* — and notes the three-genus tradition (*nās / nasnās / nasānis*, attributed to al-Jāḥiẓ). **Al-Jāḥiẓ himself rejects the three-genus theory as folk etymology** in *Kitāb al-Ḥayawān*, arising from a misreading of al-Ḥasan al-Baṣrī's saying and al-Kumayt's poem.

**The taxonomy maps onto a tripartite fate-typology:** annihilated (al-Ḥinn/al-Binn per Ibn Kathīr); displaced (the pre-Adamic jinn, still extant invisibly); transformed/*masakha* (Wabār → Nasnās, surviving in Yemen and the China-Sea islands). Modern Arab authors (Fahd al-Aḥmadī, *Riyāḍ* 2008; Shīʿī sources) explicitly draw the Neanderthal parallel — the Nasnās as the closest pre-modern Arabic concept to a parallel sapient hominid lineage.

**Confidence VH** for the textual citations; **H** for the four-layer system as a system (Ibn ʿĀshūr explicitly flags it as *"min al-mazāʿim"* — among unfounded claims, likening some names to placeholder "John Doe" expressions).

